Text: The fourth week of work on our project passed at a rapid pace .
We haven't prepared too many documents, i. e. , google drive is empty compared to previous weeks.
But as we assumed, we focused on coding.

The coding was an essential task, and we were able to achieve the assumed goal - some of the code is still very crude and requires corrections and refinement, but the main assumptions have been implemented.
So, we have a final screen with scores and a map that shows the driving road and displayed on the summarising panel with results and recommendations.
Each of us works differently:  some are more creative, others more imitative, others are switched on so that work goes smoothly forward.
But in all this, the most important thing is that you have to let go sometimes and wonder what my strengths and weaknesses are.
And instead of trying at all costs to do everything from which nothing can finally come out, be able to stop and set limits.
And rely on whoever takes care of this part accordingly.
It was so with me this week.
Not that I gave up coding : ) As I assumed, I prepared the initial screen design in RShiny - it took me some time, two sleepless nights, erasing the whole code and starting work from the beginning.
But it worked out.
It wasn't perfect, but at least I got the basics under control.
The connecting files/error summaries with displaying on the results screen were giving me also sleeplessness.
And again, Roro succored to us.
This way, on Tuesday, I had the first basic graphic version prepared in RShiny.
I started polishing the code, but playing with the rectangles, typing in the hard coding, changing colors, it can go on forever.
So I asked Tzu-Rara for help and further work on the graphic elements because I know that visualization is also an important issue for her.
I had also known, that she will prepare three other screens with a proper database.
But finally, for a moment, I felt satisfaction that something colored appears on the screen, and I know how to write the code to rearrange the elements on the screen or change the color.
I wanted still to work on the graphic code myself because it is the part that gives me the most pleasure.
Still, there were many other issues - how to add Nudges Theory to the screen, start preparing presentations, and preparing for another meeting with the focus group.
Once again, we shared the tasks and another week of work ahead of us.
Koko created a list of tasks in Trello and this tool systematizes the work to some extent or at least shows:  who is working on what.
With such a small group and quite well organized, this tool wasn't necessary despite we are an ethnic and cultural mix.
It was not required only from my point of view, but with larger groups or for people who needed a clear message, or just want to see who is at what task, such a tool is beneficial.
We had another meeting with Gfactor - we told them at what stage we are, what we will do with the upcoming week, and what was the response from the focus group during the first meeting.
Our shared goals have been achieved: .
1 / Meeting with the focus group - we received feedback on what we have prepared.
2 / Coding, coding, and re-coding - here, we have some success.
3 / Starting of preparing the presentation - draft started.
And personal: .
1 / Preparation for the INFO201 exam - I still have some lectures to listen to, but I learn more with each new one.
And here, I think about our project after listening to the last lecture.

We started work in R because at least some of the people in our group knew this language and knew that CSV files could be read in R.  We mastered RShiny to visualize the results, but we did not ask the client what programming language they use.
What system do they use?
We focused on the result and to be able to present proposals to the client.
And as far as I know, R doesn't tell them anything.
The code can be rewritten, but why double work?
It is my reflection on the next project.
Or maybe it had to be so, our client from the beginning was quite enigmatic and did not never talk about technical matters.
It is learning for the future:  ask questions!.
The goals for next week are: .
1 / code polishing,.
2 / preparing the final presentation,.
3 / preparing a document for the client describing the project,.
4 / transcripts from meetings with the focus group,.and, of course, passing the exam.
Overall
